<h2 class="section-title">

Houiyat International Festival – Founding Edition 2024

</h2>

<!-- ============================================= -->

<div class="festival-card">

<h3>

Houiyat International Festival 2024

</h3>

<p>

Afaq Tangier Association for Culture and Arts organized the Houiyat International Festival, the first forum in Morocco dedicated to young creators of both traditional and digital audiovisual content.

The festival promotes audiovisual productions that showcase Morocco's identity in all its historical depth, cultural diversity, artistic heritage, craftsmanship, investment in human and scientific development, and sustainable natural resources. It also develops research and strategies to empower an organized, creative, and culturally aware generation capable of producing content that reflects the authenticity and excellence of Moroccan identity.

</p>

<div class="festival-images">

<img src="/images/HouiyatInternationalFestival2024/photo1.jpg" alt="">
<img src="/images/HouiyatInternationalFestival2024/photo2.jpg" alt="">

</div>

</div>

<!-- ============================================= -->

<div class="festival-card">

<h3>

Day One

</h3>

<h4>

Friday, April 18, 2025

</h4>

<p>

The festival officially opened at the Boukmakh Cultural Center in Tangier.

During the morning session, a workshop entitled

<strong>

"From Idea to Image"

</strong>

was organized for school children.

The workshop welcomed:

</p>

<ul>

<li>

Approximately 400 students.

</li>

<li>

More than 50 workshop facilitators.

</li>

<li>

50 journalists and media professionals.

</li>

<li>

Nearly 100 visitors.

</li>

</ul>

<p>

The animated film

<strong>

The Eternal Procession

</strong>

directed by Omani filmmaker Salem Al Rawahi was also screened.

</p>

<p>

Media coverage was provided by:

</p>

<ul>

<li>

Al Aoula (Moroccan National TV).

</li>

<li>

The Moroccan Cultural Channel.

</li>

<li>

Tangier Regional TV.

</li>

<li>

Cap Radio.

</li>

<li>

Al Araby TV.

</li>

<li>

Al Madar TV (Belgium).

</li>

<li>

Al Bawaba Press.

</li>

<li>

Tangier & The North Newspaper.

</li>

</ul>

<p>

In the evening, an art exhibition was inaugurated featuring the works of:

</p>

<ul>

<li>

Mahassen Al Ahrash.

</li>

<li>

Aliaa Al Azzi.

</li>

</ul>

<p>

The official opening ceremony then began with a speech by Festival Director Mrs. Andalous Yassine Abdeljabbar Al Bakri, followed by speeches from guests representing Morocco, Iraq, the United Arab Emirates, the Sultanate of Oman, and Egypt. The Moroccan film "House of Poetry", directed by Malika Maa El Ainine, was then screened, and the day concluded with a Moroccan traditional fashion show and patriotic musical performances.

</p>

<div class="festival-images">

<img src="/images/day1/photo1.jpg" alt="">
<img src="/images/day1/photo2.jpg" alt="">
<img src="/images/day1/photo3.jpg" alt="">

</div>

</div>

